# Prisma & Data Layer

## Schema Conventions
- Models are `PascalCase`, singular: `Order`, not `orders`.
- Fields are `camelCase`. Use `@map` / `@@map` to keep the DB `snake_case`.
- Every foreign key has an index unless it is already part of the primary key:
  ```prisma
  @@index([userId])
  ```
- IDs: `@id @default(cuid())` by default. Use `uuid` or `autoincrement` only with a stated reason.
- Money: `Decimal @db.Decimal(18, 8)`. Never `Float`, never `Int` for fractional currency.
- Every persisted entity has `createdAt DateTime @default(now())` and `updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt`.

## Migrations
- One logical change per migration. Name: `YYYYMMDDHHMM_short_snake_case_summary`.
- Never edit an already-applied migration — create a new one.
- Destructive changes (`DROP`, rename) go in their own migration with a header comment explaining the safe-rollout plan.

## Access Rules
- `PrismaService` is only injected into `*.repository.ts` files.
- Repositories return **domain types**, not `Prisma.<Model>GetPayload<...>`. Map at the boundary.
- No `$queryRaw` unless there is a measured performance or capability reason, documented in a comment above the call.

## Example

```ts
// ✅ Repository maps to a domain type at the boundary
async findById(id: string): Promise<Order | null> {
  const row = await this.prisma.order.findUnique({ where: { id } });
  return row ? toOrder(row) : null;
}
```

## Don't
- Don't export Prisma-generated types from a module's public API.
- Don't call `prisma` from a service or controller — go through the repository.
- Don't seed production data from migration files; use a separate `prisma/seed.ts` guarded by env.
